The '''Korbut flip''' is a [[gymnastics]] skill performed on either of two different apparatuses. Both are extremely difficult and were first performed internationally by the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] [[gymnast]] [[Olga Korbut]].<ref name="BBC">{{cite news|url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/1054998/Korbut-flip|title=Korbut flip|work=[[Encyclopædia Britannica]]|accessdate=2008-08-21}}</ref>

The skill used to be able to be performed on the [[uneven bars (gymnastics)|uneven bars]], where the gymnast, from a stand on the high bar, performs a back [[somersault|flip]] and regrasps the bar.<ref name = "Wimp.com">{{cite news|url=http://www.wimp.com/unevenbars/|title=Original Olympic Video|accessdate=2011-04-29}}</ref> Korbut performed the move at the [[1972 Summer Olympics]], where it was the first backward release move performed on the uneven bars in international competition. In 1977, Soviet gymnast [[Elena Mukhina]] modified the flip by adding a full twist. The movement was later modified in the 1980s when it was performed towards the low bar; that is, the gymnast's flip takes place above the low bar. The [[Code of Points (artistic gymnastics)|Code of Points]] was later modified to make it illegal to stand on top of the bars. This move is considered highly dangerous.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Walsh|first1=Michael|title=The Korbut Flip: Dangerous move, now illegal|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/sports/olympics-2012/korbut-flip-move-dangerous-today-olympic-gymnasts-aren-allowed-attempt-article-1.1134730|accessdate=15 September 2016|work=[[New York Daily News]]|date=August 12, 2012}}</ref>

The skill is also performed on the [[balance beam]]. The move is performed from a standing position and is landed in a straddled position on the beam. This movement has been modified to include twists and piked or tucked legs and is performed in sequence with other movements.

