{{Infobox stadium | name = Pyongyang Gymnasium | nickname = | image = Laika ac Pyongyang Indoor Stadium (12144535375).jpg | caption = Exterior of the Pyongyang Gymnasium | fullname = Pyongyang Indoor Stadium | location = [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]] | pushpin_map = Pyongyang | pushpin_map_caption = Location in [[Pyongyang]] | opened = 1973 | renovated = | expanded = | surface = [[Parquet]] | construction_cost = | architect = [[Yun Ko-gwang]]<ref>{{cite magazine|author=Choe Kwang|date=April 2014|title=50-Year Devotion to Education|magazine=Democratic People's Republic of Korea|issue=700|page=29|issn=1727-9208}}</ref> | architecture_firm = | structural engineer = | services engineer = | general_contractor = | project_manager = | main_contractors = | former_names = | tenants = | capacity = 20,100 (sports and concerts) | dimensions = | scoreboard = }}
'''Pyongyang Gymnasium''', also known as '''Pyongyang Indoor Stadium''', is an [[indoor arena|indoor sporting arena]] located in [[Pyongyang]], [[North Korea]]. The capacity of the arena is for 20,100 people and was opened in 1973.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.worldstadiums.com/asia/countries/north_korea.shtml|title=World Stadiums - Stadiums in North Korea|website=www.worldstadiums.com|accessdate=1 June 2018}}</ref> It is used to host indoor sporting events, such as basketball and volleyball, as well as concerts. ==References== {{Reflist}}
